            <p>The collection is organized into the following series: I. Correspondence and II.
                Manuscripts.</p>
        </arrangement>

        <!-- required for collection level; optional for lower levels -->
        <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">

            <head>Scope and Content Note</head>
            <p>Consists of correspondence and manuscripts of Gary James Scrimgeour, 1934- ,
                primarily relating to the writing and publication of Scrimgeour's first novel, <emph
                    render="italic">A Woman of Her Times</emph>. Correspondents include publisher
                Frank Eugene Taylor, <unitdate normal="1916/1999" type="inclusive"
                    >1916-1999,</unitdate> who acted as Scrimgeour's agent in selling the manuscript
                of <emph render="italic">A Woman of Her Times</emph>, as well as editors at Michael
                Joseph Ltd. in London and G.P. Putnam's Sons in New York, publishers of the novel.
                Also included is a draft of Scrimgeour's <unitdate normal="1968">1968</unitdate>
                dissertation for Princeton University, <emph render="italic">Drama and Theatre in
                    the Early Nineteenth Century</emph>. Completing the collection are notes and
                manuscripts on 19th century drama and dramatists, an unrealized series of
                publications prepared in the <unitdate normal="1970/1979" type="inclusive"
                    >1970s</unitdate> for Ben Blom, Inc.</p>
        </scopecontent>

